{
  "id": "019d317e-1525-7bf2-8f89-bce6fff8ce29",
  "content": "# Agentic Retrieval Protocol — Architecture Decision (2026-03-27)\n\n## Decision\nServer-side intelligence over agent instructions. Complex retrieval logic (quality assessment, gap detection, query reformulation hints, write dedup) lives in corvia's MCP tools. Agent instructions are minimal (~20 lines in AGENTS.md).\n\n## Why\n- LLM self-assessment is ~70% reliable (KDD 2025 survey)\n- Explicit gap reporting has <20% compliance across memory frameworks (Mem0, Letta, Zep research)\n- More AGENTS.md instructions past a threshold = lower compliance\n- Simple unconditional rules get followed consistently across Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, Copilot\n\n## Key Patterns\n1. Search responses include `confidence` + `suggestion` fields — agent follows suggestion, doesn't reason about quality\n2. Context injection via `corvia_context` with token budget param — universal subagent pattern\n3. Implicit gap detection from search logs — no agent action required\n4. Implicit feedback via access tracking (issue #12) — no explicit ratings\n5. Server-side write dedup (similarity > 0.9) — prevents bloat without agent burden\n\n## Dropped\n- Time-based write triggers (not implementable)\n- Write reminders / server push (MCP is request-response)\n- Explicit result ratings (unreliable compliance)\n\n## Issue\nchunzhe10/corvia#47",
